Proses, the Sequences of a later date, from a Troper in the Bodleian Library, written sometime during the reign of Etheldred‚ and later than the Canonization of S. Ethelwold.

This is certainly the earliest known collection of Sequenoes: fifty-five of thern do not appear in any printed collection to which I have had access.

This MS. is the only English Troper known to exist. There was once an English Troper in the Ohurch of S. Bavon at Ghent. This is described by Pamelius in his “ Liturgicon‚'' and a few Tropesaragiven. The MS. cannot now be found. It does not appear to have contained any Sequences. The Bodleian MS. is described by Mr. Maskell, “Ritualia Ecclesiae Anglicanee,'' vol. i. pp. xxxin-xli, and very fully by Dr. Book, “Ohurch of our Fathers‚’' vol iii. part ii. 20-28.

I have printed the Proses from this volume, as the earliest collection of those used in the Ohurch oi England, and also as there appears good reason for believing with Dr. Roek that a large portion at least of these Proses were written by Alcuin.
